    "en": "Abiotic (Non-Infectious) Diseases in Cambodian Agriculture: The Silent Limiter of Crop Potential",
    "ja": null,
    "latex": null,
    "preview_source": "tier7-ingest-v0.2",
    "summary": "Abstract Abiotic disorders, stemming from non-living environmental and management stressors, constitute a pervasive and often misdiagnosed constraint on crop productivity in Cambodia. Unlike biotic diseases, these conditions are not contagious but are systemic responses to suboptimal growth environments, including nutrient deficiencies, water extremes (flooding and drought), soil acidity, pesticide phytotoxicity, and increasing heat stress. These disorders are frequently mistaken for pathogen-induced diseases, leading to inappropriate management responses, such as unnecessary pesticide applications, which exacerbate the problem and increase production costs. This review synthesizes current knowledge on the major abiotic stressors affecting Cambodian cropping systems, their symptomatic expr"
